<span class="section-label">About the project</span>
<div class="description">
  <p>
    In late 2012, BMW unveiled their new line of electric vehicles with an installation at one of the most trafficked intersections in Manhattan. The concept was deceptively simple: transform a storefront window so that instead of reflecting the noise and traffic of 42nd Street, passersby saw BMW's electric vehicles navigating a cleaner, quieter version of the same city.
  </p>
  <p>
    The execution was anything but simple. A Kinect sensor detected pedestrians on the sidewalk, allowing them to interact with the vehicles through the glass — gesturing, exploring, watching the cars respond in real time. Scale, weather exposure, and the sheer chaos of Midtown all had to be engineered around.
  </p>
  <p>
    The installation ran live during the BMW Electric Car Event, and stopped traffic in the most literal sense. It went live two days after Hurricane Sandy had wrecked the city. Without an incident.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="field-notes">
  <span class="section-label">Field notes</span>
  <div class="field-notes-body">
    <p>
      Before the go-live, the agency partners pulled me aside. BMW was one of their most important clients. If the installation failed — technically, logistically, publicly — it was going to be very bad for the company. I was the one with hands on the hardware. That weight lands differently in person.
    </p>
    <p>
      I was so nervous the morning of the launch, I got physically sick. Then the system came up clean. The Kinect tracked. The projection locked. People on the sidewalk stopped and interacted. I watched a woman in a raincoat gesture at a car through a window in a city that had flooded two days earlier, and it worked exactly as intended.
    </p>
    <p>
      That's what shipping hardware into the wild actually looks like.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
